MODULE 2.1: DISCOUNTED CASH FLOW (DCF) VALUATION

What Is ‚ÄúDiscounted Cash Flow‚Äù (DCF)?
‚ÄúMoney you will get in the future is worth less than money you have today.‚Äù

This is because of opportunity cost‚Äîyou could use or invest today‚Äôs money to grow more.

DCF helps you calculate:
"How much is ‚Çπ100 that I‚Äôll get in 3 years worth today?"

The Formula:
If you expect to receive ‚Çπ100 in 1 year, and interest rate is 10%:

üí° Present Value (PV) = ‚Çπ100 √∑ (1 + 10%) = ‚Çπ100 √∑ 1.10 = ‚Çπ90.91
This means:

‚Çπ100 in 1 year is worth ‚Çπ90.91 today
(if you could earn 10% interest elsewhere)

DCF for Different Investments:
1. Zero-Coupon Bond
No interest payments

Only pays one big amount at maturity

üßæ Example:
If you‚Äôll get ‚Çπ1,000 after 3 years, and rate = 6%:

PV = ‚Çπ1,000 √∑ (1 + 6%)¬≥ = ‚Çπ839.62
So, you‚Äôll pay ‚Çπ839.62 today to get ‚Çπ1,000 after 3 years.

2. Coupon Bond
(This pays interest every year)

Suppose it gives ‚Çπ100 per year for 3 years

Plus ‚Çπ1,000 at the end (final payment)

You discount each payment separately:

Year 1: ‚Çπ100 √∑ (1 + r)^1

Year 2: ‚Çπ100 √∑ (1 + r)^2

Year 3: ‚Çπ1,100 √∑ (1 + r)^3
(Add them all = total value today)

3. Preferred Stock (fixed dividend forever)
Like a bond but no maturity ‚Äî just regular payments

üßæ Example:

Pays ‚Çπ8 every year, forever

Market wants a 10% return

PV = ‚Çπ8 √∑ 10% = ‚Çπ80
So, this stock is worth ‚Çπ80 today.

4. Common Stock (dividends may grow)
If dividend grows every year, use this:

PV = Dividend next year √∑ (Return % ‚àí Growth %)

üßæ Example:

Next year‚Äôs dividend = ‚Çπ2

Expected return = 12%, Growth = 4%

PV = ‚Çπ2 √∑ (12% ‚àí 4%) = ‚Çπ2 √∑ 0.08 = ‚Çπ25

5. Loan Payments (Annuity)
If you borrow ‚Çπ2,000 and repay over 5 years with equal payments and 6% interest:

Use the calculator or formula to find payment = ‚Çπ473.86
Each payment includes part interest + part principal.

üß† Key Takeaway
DCF helps you figure out how much future cash is worth today.

Whether it‚Äôs a bond, stock, or loan ‚Äî if money is coming (or going) in the future, DCF tells you how much to pay or expect today.

