MODULE 2.2: IMPLIED RETURNS AND CASH FLOW ADDITIVITY
This module focuses on two things:

How to calculate the return (interest rate) an investment is giving you ‚Äî even if it‚Äôs not directly stated.

Why we can simply ‚Äúadd‚Äù future cash flows to get the total value ‚Äî this is called the cash flow additivity principle.

Implied Return ‚Äì What Return Am I Getting?
üí° What does "implied" mean?
It means the return isn‚Äôt given to you directly, but you can calculate it from the price and cash flows.

üßæ Example: Zero-Coupon Bond
You buy a bond for ‚Çπ650 today.
It pays you ‚Çπ1,000 after 5 years.

You want to know: ‚ÄúWhat return am I getting?‚Äù

Cash Flow Additivity Principle
üí° Simple Definition:
‚ÄúThe value of a bunch of future cash flows = the sum of the value of each cash flow.‚Äù

üßæ Why is this useful?
Because you can break big cash flows into smaller parts, and add them back up. It still gives the same value.

üßæ Example:
You‚Äôre promised:

‚Çπ100 in 1 year

‚Çπ200 in 2 years

‚Çπ300 in 3 years

Discount rate = 10%

You calculate the present value (PV) of each:

‚Çπ100 √∑ (1.10)^1 = ‚Çπ90.91

‚Çπ200 √∑ (1.10)^2 = ‚Çπ165.29

‚Çπ300 √∑ (1.10)^3 = ‚Çπ225.39

Add all the PVs:

Total PV = ‚Çπ481.59

This is the value today of all those future cash flows.

üîÅ Why is this powerful?
It‚Äôs the basis for:

Bond pricing

Loan valuation

Stock valuation

Option pricing

Forward contracts

All these use the same idea: Break cash flows ‚Üí Discount them ‚Üí Add them

‚úÖ Real-World Uses of Additivity
1. Forward Interest Rates
If you know today's interest rates for 1 year and 2 years, you can use them to find the interest rate for Year 2 only.

2. Currency Forward Rates
If you know interest rates in India and the US, and today‚Äôs USD/INR rate, you can calculate the future USD/INR rate ‚Äî to avoid arbitrage (risk-free profit).

3. Option Pricing (Binomial Models)
Even complex things like stock options use this ‚Äî break possible outcomes into pieces, discount them, and add.

